          <subparagraph>
            <content>
              <p><b>VI. Risks and assumptions</b></p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <content>
              <p><u>Potential policy risks</u></p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <content>
              <p><i>Moving, but not reducing, illegitimate activity</i></p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>112.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Increased scrutiny at the registration stage together with the ability to deregister LPs should deter the use of illegitimate activity. However, closing one avenue for illegitimate activity always bears the risk that criminal activity will not fundamentally be stopped, but just moved, with criminals potentially using different corporate vehicles either inside or outside the UK.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>113.</num>
          <content>
            <p>There are a number of other countries which have vehicles similar to an LP.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>Figure 13: Comparative corporate bodies</b></p>
            <table uk:widths="1.18in 1.69in 1.69in 1.69in">
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Countries/ partnership type</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Societe en commandite simple (Lux LP) and Societe en commandite special (Lux SLP)</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Delaware LP</b><authorialNote marker="37"><p class="ia-table-text"> See: <a href="http://delcode.delaware.gov/title6/c017/index.html"><u>http://delcode.delaware.gov/title6/c017/index.html</u></a><u> </u></p></authorialNote></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Jersey &amp; Guernsey</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Partnership type</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Like the (S)LP, the Lux (S)LP have at least one limited and unlimited partner and have flexibility regarding the vehicle’s organisation and functioning</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">The partnership is a separate legal entity.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text" />
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Public Disclosures</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Unlike SLPs, the Lux equivalents do not require the names of the limited partners and their contributions, as well as transfers of LP interests<authorialNote marker="38"><p class="ia-table-text">See: <a href="https://www.pwc.lu/en/private-equity/current-challenges-luxembourg-limited-partnership.html"><u>https://www.pwc.lu/en/private-equity/current-challenges-luxembourg-limited-partnership.html</u></a>  </p></authorialNote></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">A Delaware LP does not have to register the names of its partners on formation.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">A non-public register of limited partnerships must be kept but is not provided to the registrar<authorialNote marker="39"><p class="ia-table-text"> The department’s correspondence with BVCA</p></authorialNote></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><i>Legitimate activity moving overseas</i></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>114.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We are aware from feedback received during the call for evidence that legitimate users, especially in the investment community, could use alternative vehicles available outside the UK. These often have even lower levels of transparency and a significant move towards overseas vehicles would harm the UK’s reputation as a leading place for private equity and venture capital. We do not think that the proposals would impose any significant additional burden on such legitimate users that would cause a significant shift in behaviour.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><i>Unintended consequences</i></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>115.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We have engaged heavily with stakeholders inside and outside government to minimise the risk that the proposed reforms could cause any unintended consequences. For example, the investment community has raised concerns that accidental deregistration of a legitimate and active LP could result in partners losing their limited liability, which could have significant consequences. We believe that the deregistration procedures as proposed would mitigate such risks and would not expose partners to any significant new risk, as the Registrar would be required to follow a robust notification procedure and ensuring any general and limited partners of an LP are given due notice of any deregistration consideration.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><u>Uncertainties in the economic assessment</u></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><i>Number of active LPs </i></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>116.</num>
          <content>
            <p>A particular uncertainty is that the number of active LPs remains unknown, as minimal information is required of them following registration, therefore we have used best estimates based on Companies House analysis in this Impact Assessment. Following implementation, we will be able to gather more accurate figures surrounding this, which will inform any future assessments of this policy. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_42">
        <heading>VII. Wider impacts</heading>
        <content>
          <p><b>VII. Wider impacts</b></p>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_43">
        <heading>Equalities assessment</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Equalities assessment</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>117.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>The Equality Act 2010 protects against unlawful discrimination on the basis of the following protected characteristics:</p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Age</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Disability</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Gender reassignment</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Marriage and civil partnership</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Pregnancy and maternity</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Race</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Religion or belief</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Sex and sexual orientation</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>118.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy is subject to the public sector equality duties set out in the Equality Act 2010. It requires public bodies to have due regard to the need to:</p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Eliminate unlawful discrimination, harassment, victimisation and any other conduct prohibited by the Act</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Advance equality of opportunity<b> </b>between people who share a protected characteristic and those who do not, and</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Foster good relations between people who share a protected characteristic and those who do not</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>119.</num>
          <content>
            <p>An equality analysis is an important mechanism for ensuring that we gather data to enable us to identify the likely positive and negative impacts that policy proposals may have on certain groups and to estimate whether such impacts disproportionately affect such groups.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><u>Aim one: eliminate unlawful discrimination, harassment, victimisation and any other conduct prohibited by the Act</u></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>120.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We do not believe that this proposal is likely to affect any of the protected groups disproportionately, as this should only affect law abiding citizens minimally and only in their professional capacity. We do not believe that anyone who is acting legitimately would be affected significantly.  </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>121.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We are aware this corporate vehicle is heavily used by citizens of certain jurisdictions, but as we have said previously, we believe that the overall impacts on legitimate users will be largely minimal.<authorialNote marker="40"><p> See: <a href="https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2017/11/14/british-governments-attempts-fight-corruption-money-laundering-already-failing/"><u>https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2017/11/14/british-governments-attempts-fight-corruption-money-laundering-already-failing/</u></a></p></authorialNote> We would also like to note that making the corporate framework more credible will make it easier for legitimate users from those jurisdictions to avoid suffering reputational damage. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><u>Aim two: advance equality of opportunity between people who share a protected characteristic and those who do not</u></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>122.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Our assessment for aim one largely applies here as well. The company law framework, and the way corporate bodies interact with Companies House, applies equally to all corporate entities to build, and maintain the overall integrity of the framework. We have not identified any existing barriers to individuals within the framework, and the proposals assessed here do not impose any new barriers on the individual level that would affect individuals or groups with protected characteristics disproportionately.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><u>Aim three: foster good relations between people who share a protected characteristic and those who do not</u></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>123.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Again, our assessment for aim one also applies here.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_44">
        <heading>Competition and innovation impact test</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Competition and innovation impact test</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>124.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The proposed reforms affect only LPs to bring them in line with other company requirements, and we thus have not identified any specific competition and innovation impacts. The proposals will help strengthen the position and protect consumers and businesses who ‘do the right thing’ from those who aim to abuse the current corporate framework.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>125.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The 2018 BEIS commissioned research on the value of the companies register found that of the businesses surveyed, 86% used company information to confirm basic information about a company, 71% to carry out due diligence work about a company and 28% to check risk/creditworthiness of a supplier.<authorialNote marker="41"><p> See: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/companies-house-data-valuing-the-user-benefits"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/companies-house-data-valuing-the-user-benefits</u></a> </p></authorialNote> By having more up to date, accurate data on the companies register it should support business when transacting with one another and thus promote competitive business taking place. Similarly, having more reliable and trustworthy data on the companies register should support business and thus have a positive impact on innovation.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_45">
        <heading>Families’ assessment</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Families’ assessment</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>126.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The policy aims ensure LPs are transparent and in line with other company law frameworks. There is no evidence for any direct impacts on family formation, on families going through key transitions such as becoming parents, or on the ability of family members to play a full role in family life. There is also no evidence that it will specifically affect those families most at risk of deterioration of relationship quality and breakdown.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_46">
        <heading>Environmental impacts</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Environmental impacts</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>127.</num>
          <content>
            <p>There are no obvious direct concerns in this area. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_47">
        <heading>Human rights</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Human rights</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>128.</num>
          <content>
            <p>It is likely that these reforms will engage the European Convention on Human Rights (Art 8 – private life; Art 1 of Protocol 1 – free enjoyment of property). BEIS Legal will conduct Human Rights analysis in due course which will set out the precise areas in which the reforms give rise to human rights interferences, and the bases on which those interferences can be justified as necessary and proportionate and thus lawful. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_48">
        <heading>Justice system</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Justice system</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>129.</num>
          <content>
            <p>A Justice Impact Test (JIT) is the Ministry of Justice tool that helps policymakers across government find the best way of achieving their policy aims whilst minimising the impact on the justice system. A JIT has been submitted to the Ministry of Justice. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_49">
        <heading>Small and micro businesses assessment</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Small and micro businesses assessment </b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>130.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The standard definition of small and micro businesses does not apply neatly to LPs because these partnerships are often better characterised as contractual agreements between businesses for a specific economic activity rather than a business. Although an LP may appear in a similar structure to a small business, with one general and limited partner, like that of a director in a company, they can be vastly different. The partners are often other vehicles themselves, and in many instances used for investment purposes. The concept of employees, therefore, does not often apply.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>131.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Due to limited reporting requirements, we cannot readily provide an assessment of sizes of LPs.<authorialNote marker="42"><p> We attempted to do so using the FAME database but were unable to clearly identify LPs which were ‘small’ using the same definition as companies. Due to limited reporting requirement this led to low values being returned.</p></authorialNote> However, where they are used for the purpose of investment vehicles, the sums involved will often mean that these partnerships could not reasonably be described as “small”, and individual investment companies involved are typically also large. We have indeed argued that LPs are often used within significant fund structures. However, when used in private-equity and venture capital those companies benefitting from the investment will sometimes be start-ups at the early stage of their development, which could well be “small”. And where limited partnerships are still used in the agricultural sector, they are likely to be used by small businesses (farms).</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>132.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Whilst we thus acknowledge that limited partnerships will in some instances be used by small and micro businesses, and that small and micro businesses can benefit from investment originating from fund structurers using LPs, we do not have robust data to provide a more detailed assessment. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>133.</num>
          <content>
            <p>In any case, the exemption of small and micro businesses would not be feasible as it would undermine the overarching policy objective of increasing transparency and reducing the likelihood of misuse of limited partnership structures. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_50">
        <heading>VIII.       Monitoring and evaluation</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>VIII.       Monitoring and evaluation</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>134.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The department, working with Companies House, will monitor LPs following the reform. By increasing the transparency surrounding LPs, we will be able to observe how many EWNILPs are active and gather further information about them.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>135.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We will also continue working with stakeholders in this area to gather an understanding on how the reforms have affected them directly. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><u>Costs to businesses</u></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>136.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We will monitor and evaluate whether the costs to business estimated were reflective of the impact on business. We will continue to engage with key stakeholders to do this as well as analyse Companies House data e.g. the number of active LPs, to review our estimates of the current stock and future flow on the register.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><u>Benefits to businesses of the proposals</u></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>137.</num>
          <content>
            <p>As outlined in <b>part V</b> the key benefits are better quality data to support transparency and supporting the prevention of economic crime.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>138.</num>
          <content>
            <p>By increasing the transparency around LPs, there will be greater and more accurate information available on the register, allowing businesses and individuals a greater level of trust in the information provided. We can measure this by the number of LPs on the register who present the required information.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>139.</num>
          <content>
            <p>When looking at deterrent and disruption of criminal use of LPs, while ensuring there is only minimal disruption to legitimate users, we will work with stakeholders, particularly law enforcement on whether the proposals have supported the prevention of economic crime. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><u>Measuring risk and unintended consequences</u></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>140.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The monitoring and evaluation process will also seek to monitor and understand any unintended consequences from implementation and the impacts of these.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_51">
        <heading>Annex Amendments made during Bill passage</heading>
        <content>
          <p><b>Annex: Amendments made during Bill passage</b></p>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_52">
        <heading>Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act</heading>
        <content>
          <p><b>Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act</b></p>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_53">
        <heading>Summary of Amendments made to DBT Measures</heading>
        <content>
          <p><b>Summary of Amendments made to DBT Measures</b></p>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_54">
        <heading>September 2024</heading>
        <content>
          <p><b>September 2024</b></p>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_55">
        <heading>Background</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Background</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>1.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act received Royal Assent in October 2023.<authorialNote marker="43"><p> See: <a href="https://bills.parliament.uk/bills/3339"><u>https://bills.parliament.uk/bills/3339</u></a> </p></authorialNote> The Act gives powers to make significant reforms to Companies House and increases transparency of UK companies. It aims to: prevent the misuse of UK registered entities (including limited partnerships), improve the accuracy of information held at Companies House and provide additional powers to seize crypto assets quicker and easier.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>2.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Overall, the role of the Act is to strengthen the UK’s response to economic crime through preventing the misuse of UK registered entities in illicit activities and improving the reliability of the data available on the companies register.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>3.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>Two final stage Impact Assessments for the Department for Business and Trade’s (DBT) measures, were published at the Act’s introduction:<authorialNote marker="44"><p> See: <a href="https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/bills/cbill/58-03/0154/1.ImpactAssessmentfromDepartmentforBusinessEnergyandIndustrialStrategy.pdf"><u>https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/bills/cbill/58-03/0154/1.ImpactAssessmentfromDepartmentforBusinessEnergyandIndustrialStrategy.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote></p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <intro>
              <p><b>Corporate Transparency and Companies House Register Reform: </b></p>
            </intro>
            <subparagraph>
              <content>
                <p>Introduce identity verification, widen Companies House powers to query/investigate information they receive and improve the quality of information available to users of the register. The net cost to business per year was assessed at £18.9m (2023 base year, 2019 prices). Around 80% of these costs were due to the introduction of identity verification, as it will impact almost 7 million individuals already on the register.</p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><b>Reform of Limited Partnership Law:</b> Tighten registration requirements, require limited partnerships to demonstrate a firmer connection to the UK, increase transparency requirements and enable the Registrar to strike from the register limited partnerships which are dissolved or which are no longer carrying on business. The net cost to business per year was assessed at £2.2m (2023 base year, 2019 prices).</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>4.</num>
          <content>
            <p class="ia-title">Impact Assessments from other departments, including the Home Office, the Ministry of Justice, and His Majesty’s Treasury were published alongside this at the Bill’s introduction.<authorialNote marker="45"><p> See: <a href="https://bills.parliament.uk/bills/3339/publications"><u>https://bills.parliament.uk/bills/3339/publications</u></a> </p><p>Overarching Home Office Impact Assessment reference is HO0413</p></authorialNote></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_56">
        <heading>Focus of this document</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Focus of this document </b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>5.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Throughout the Bill’s passage through Parliament, various amendments were made to the legislation. As per the Better Regulation Framework: <i>“Enactment IAs are required only for primary legislation that has been amended in its passage through Parliament in such a way as to significantly change the impacts of the policy on business […] If the impacts of the Act remain unchanged then an enactment IA is not necessary.”</i> <authorialNote marker="46"><p> See: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/better-regulation-framework"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/better-regulation-framework</u></a></p></authorialNote></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>6.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Following our assessment of these amendments, we <u>do not</u> believe that the primary legislation has been amended in such a way that significantly changes the impacts of the policy on business. <u>As a result, </u><i><u>a full enactment Impact Assessment has not been produced</u></i><i>. </i>It is possible that as a result of further work on secondary legislation or during Companies House implementation that our assessment of costs and benefits will change. This will be reflected in any Impact Assessments accompanying regulations.  </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>7.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Summarised below are all of the amendments (with respect to DBT’s measures) made at each stage of the Bill’s passage through Parliament, as well as the supporting cost assessment for each:</p>
            <table uk:widths="3.15in 3.93in">
              <tr>
                <td colspan="2">
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Commons Committee and Report Stage Amendments</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Amendment</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Cost Assessment on Business</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">A small number of minor and technical amendments to address drafting deficiencies</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text" />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">A small number of minor and technical amendments to address drafting deficiencies and complete the legislation. For instance, replacing references to ‘companies’ with ‘body corporate’.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">These amendments were only used to complete the existing legislation and pose no direct cost to business.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments needed to align the Register of Overseas Entities with Companies House reform and to better implement the Register of Overseas Entities.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">As far as possible, the requirements of the Register of Overseas Entities mirror the equivalent requirements for the Persons with Significant Control of UK companies. Where ‘mirrored’ provisions are changing as a result of Companies House reform, we will assess whether an equivalent change is required to the Register of Overseas Entities. Any differences in approach will reflect the different requirements on overseas entities compared with UK companies.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">These may pose a very small additional cost to each overseas business in scope, but overall costs are unlikely to be significant given the share of entities affected by this amendment – ~31,000 overseas entities vs. 4.9 million companies.<authorialNote marker="47"><p class="ia-table-text"> Companies register activities (Statistical release April 2023 to March 2024): <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/companies-register-activities-statistical-release-april-2023-to-march-2024"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/companies-register-activities-statistical-release-april-2023-to-march-2024</u></a> </p></authorialNote></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Introducing a requirement for the Government to publish an annual report on implementation of Companies House Reforms.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Publishing an annual report is a cost to government and will not directly impact business.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Removal of some of the identity verification exemptions for directors</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment removed a regulation making power that could be used to exempt categories of directors from identity verification requirements as the power was assessed as being unlikely to be used, and therefore removed from the Act. This has no cost impact on businesses. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Requirements relating to the dissolution, revival, deregistration, winding up and sequestration of limited partnerships </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This will allow limited partnerships (LPs) that are both solvent and insolvent to be:</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• dissolved, </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• wound up on petition to the High Court or Court of Session (if registered in Scotland), </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• sequestrated (if registered in Scotland), </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• administratively revived to the register, </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• deregistered, </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• removed from the index of names held by the registrar</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Internal analysis suggests there are only 18,000 <u>active</u> LPs.<authorialNote marker="48"><p class="ia-table-text"> Whilst There are roughly 58,000 Limited Partnerships on the register, this also includes limited partnerships that are closed as they have not been removed from the register. We have done some further analysis to estimate the share of these entities that are active. See the methodology used here: The Registrar (Identity Verification and Authorised Corporate Service Providers) Regulations 2024 pg. 24: <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukdsi/2024/9780348261905/impacts/2024/96"><u>https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukdsi/2024/9780348261905/impacts/2024/96</u></a> </p></authorialNote> Any LPs that are solvent are making a choice to dissolve and can most likely bear any costs involved. LPs that are insolvent are most likely being dissolved or wound up due to non-compliance. Any costs incurred from non-compliance would fall out of scope of our analysis. As a result, we assess no direct cost to business.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Strengthening the range of sanctions for non-compliance with the Register of Overseas Entities</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment includes the following:</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Enforcement of requirement to register: updated language about penalties etc</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text" />
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Financial penalties: interaction with offences</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">These amendments will only directly impact businesses who have been sanctioned due to non-compliance. Therefore, we do not consider it within our cost assessment. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
            <table uk:widths="3.15in 3.93in">
              <tr>
                <td colspan="2">
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Lords Committee Stage Amendments</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Amendment</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Cost Assessment on Business</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to strengthen the Registrar’s objectives (e.g. the new role of the company registrar) and power to require information</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment provides the registrar with more power to query/challenge information. The vast majority of companies burdened by this would be those which have chosen to file incorrect information on purpose or even with criminal intent and therefore out of scope of our analysis.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Any costs incurred from non-compliance are not considered in our cost assessment.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to strengthen shareholder transparency</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment provides a more effective legal framework for companies/members to follow. </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">These amendments included the following:</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">a) New powers allowing companies to obtain information from their members and ensure it is kept up to date, and new duties for members to provide this information and keep it up to date</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">b) New offences for members and companies who fail to do so without a reasonable excuse</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">c) New power for the Secretary of State to make regulations to allow people to apply to “protect” information from being publicly available in the company’s register of members </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">A comprehensive assessment will be undertaken if the Government chose to exercise this power. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to address interplays between director disqualification measures and the sanctions regime</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment achieved the following:</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Created a new type of sanction in the Sanctions and Anti-Money Laundering Act 2018 called director disqualification sanctions.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Ensured consistency between Great Britain and Northern Ireland legislation regarding director disqualification sanctions measure.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment will impact individuals who have been disqualified for failing to comply with requirements. Any costs which arise would be from non-compliance, which we do not consider when assessing the cost to businesses.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to extend the application of company director disqualification provisions to other entities in Northern Ireland</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text" />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Provided powers to make regulations to amend the Company Directors Disqualification Act 1986 and the Company Directors Disqualification (Northern Ireland) Order 2002. The regulations will widen the scope of the legislation to apply to other relevant entities, such as limited partnerships.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Costs will only arise as a result of non-compliance and, as a result fall out of scope of our analysis.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments addressing the interaction between the disqualification regime and general partners/registered officers in limited partnerships</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This extends the disqualification regime to general partners and registered officers of limited partnerships.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Any costs which arise would be from non-compliance, which we do not consider when assessing the cost to businesses.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to the Register of Overseas entities, including the power to amend the Economic Crime (Transparency and Enforcement) Act 2022 in line with amendments to the Companies Act 2006, an amendment to the verification process, and introducing an anti-avoidance measure to capture changes in beneficial ownership from 28 February 2022 to registration or the end of the transitional period.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Overseas entities that sell properties or make any other disposition of land in scope of the Register of Overseas Entities (ROE) requirements (such as leases or charges) between 28 February 2022 and either their application for registration or the end of the transitional period, are obligated to submit their beneficial ownership details as at the point of disposition, along with details of the relevant properties. </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Businesses may incur a cost, however this is unlikely to be very burdensome. Ultimately, overseas entities only represent a small subset of the entire business population (31,000 overseas entities vs. 4.9 million companies), therefore the cost of this amendment will be minimal overall.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">The verification process for ROE may be amended. The details of this will be outlined in secondary legislation. We will consider whether this will lead to a significant change in our original cost estimates at this time.  </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
            <table uk:widths="3.15in 3.93in">
              <tr>
                <td colspan="2">
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Lords Report Stage Amendments</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Amendment</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Cost Assessment on Business</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">A new power providing scope to make regulations enabling the Registrar to prevent information from the profit and loss accounts of small companies and micro-entities being made available for public inspection</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">The power could be used to withhold all information from all profit and loss accounts from the public register, some information for all profit and loss accounts, or some information from the profit and loss accounts of some companies. It could also be implemented on application or automatically. The combination chosen, if the power is used at all, will ultimately impact the cost of implementation. </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Due to this uncertainty surrounding implementation and the lack of relevant evidence, we cannot assess the possible cost on business. We will look at updating this analysis if this power is ultimately used. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments related to Authorised Corporate Service Providers (ACSPs) and those who are to have authority to deliver documents to the Registrar.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">In combination these amendments:</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">1. Permitted verification statements delivered by ACSPs to confirm they have verified their client’s identity to be published on the register. The verification statement will include the name of the ACSPs and their supervisory authority. </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">2. Clarified that regulations could be made to allow the Registrar to require information from ACSPs relating to identity verification checks</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">3. Restricted who could file information with Companies House to prevent unauthorised corporate service providers from being able to file, and</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">4. Introduced a ‘negative fit and proper person’ test as part of the authorisation process for ACSPs.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">1, 2 and 4 do not have an additional regulatory cost to business as they will be delivered by Companies House. 3 may have a cost to businesses or ACSPs who need to change their employment or company arrangements in order to use the current filing gateways. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to the director disqualification sanction regime and financial penalties.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment clarified when a person subject to director disqualification sanctions, or a person acting on the instructions of such an individual, is responsible for the debts of a company. The Department for the Economy in Northern Ireland will be required to maintain information about individuals subject to the new director disqualification sanctions in the Department’s register of disqualified directors. This mirrors the requirement for the Secretary of State to update the UK-wide Director Disqualification Register ensuring consistency between GB and NI legislation.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Where a person commits an offence, they may have either a financial penalty imposed upon them or be prosecuted criminally. Costs only apply to businesses which are non-compliant, which is outside of the scope for our cost assessment.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to increase access to information on overseas ownership of property via trusts, to further improve the transparency of the Register of Overseas Entities</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment introduced a new power for the Secretary of State to make regulations that set out the criteria under which the Registrar is required, on successful application, to disclose ROE trusts information. As the information is already collected, this will not directly have any costs to business. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to require more information to be provided about trust beneficiaries when an overseas entity submits an annual update, or a removal application to the Register of Overseas Entities.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment requires an overseas entity that has a beneficial owner, who is a trustee, to provide information about in-year changes to trust beneficiaries during the update period - instead of only providing a snapshot of the beneficiaries of the trust at the time that the update is made.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Businesses may incur a cost, however any costs are likely to be minimal. Much of this information is already held by these entities, therefore gathering and/or submitting this information is unlikely to pose significant additional burden.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
            <table uk:widths="3.15in 3.93in">
              <tr>
                <td colspan="2">
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Lords Third Reading Amendments</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Amendment</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Cost Assessment on Business</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to require companies to collect additional information about their PSCs</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Currently, a company must keep a local PSC register <i>and</i> provide the information contained within it to Companies House. The requirements to keep a local PSC register have been removed as part of the Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act 2023, so a company will only have to provide this information to Companies House. There have also been several amendments to the way in which companies determine who their PSCs are and how the notify Companies House.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment will apply to all companies and therefore will impact almost 5 million companies.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">The primary cost comes from these entities needing to familiarise themselves with this policy change. We assess a cost of £8.40 per entity - £40.3m for all 4.8 million entities. However, if every company were to save <u>at least</u> £0.84 per year from no longer holding a local register, over a 10-year appraisal period they would recoup their initial cost.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><i><u>Refer to the Appendix A for further details of this cost assessment.</u></i></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to align the drafting of false statement offences relating to the PSCs of UK companies with other similar offences in the ECCT Act 23</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment will impact those who have submitted a false statement. Therefore, costs only apply to businesses which are non-compliant and outside of our scope of cost to business.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to close a gap by which the requirements of the Register of Overseas Entities can be circumvented by the use of a nominee arrangement.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">The new provision requires that where an overseas entity holds land in the UK for another person in its capacity as a nominee, the other person is to be treated as a registrable beneficial owner of the nominee, thereby requiring the provision of information about them. Thereby closing the gap where those using the services of a nominee to hold land in the UK could avoid having their details disclosed to Companies House. It’s possible some costs may arise for businesses (i.e. gathering/ providing information on a nominee). However, this amendment only affects a small proportion of the company population (31,000 overseas entities vs. 4.9 million companies registered with Companies House) so any costs that do arise are likely to be minimal overall. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
            <table uk:widths="3.15in 3.93in">
              <tr>
                <td colspan="2">
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Lords Consideration of Commons Amendments Round 1 (LCCA1) Amendment</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Amendment</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Cost Assessment on Business</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">A new power to impose further duties involving nominee shareholders</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment allows the Secretary of State to make regulations to make further provision for the purpose of enabling a company to find out who its Persons of Significant Control are in cases where shares are held by a nominee. This could include, amongst other things: imposing further obligations on companies to find out if they have nominee shareholders, and if so, for whom they are holding shares; or imposing further obligations on nominee shareholders to disclose their status, and for whom they are holding shares.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Further details are required to undertake a comprehensive cost assessment alongside subsequent secondary legislation. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><b><u>Appendix A: </u></b><b><u>Amendments to require companies to collect additional information about their PSCs</u></b></p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_57">
        <heading>Background</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Background</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>1.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The PSC register is a register of beneficial owners of UK companies. It was launched in 2016 following the introduction through the Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015 which amended the Companies Act 2006. The information on the register is publicly accessible and free of charge. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>2.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Currently, a company must keep a local PSC register <i>and</i> provide the information contained within it to Companies House. The requirements to keep a local PSC register have been removed as part of the Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act 2023, so a company will only have to provide this information to Companies House. There have also been several amendments to the way in which companies determine who their PSCs are and how the notify Companies House.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_58">
        <heading>Costs</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Costs</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>3.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Since this amendment will apply to all companies, all directors must familiarise themselves with the policy change. At the end of December 2023, there were 4.8 million on the effective register.<authorialNote marker="49"><p> See: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/incorporated-companies-in-the-uk-october-to-december-2023/incorporated-companies-in-the-uk-october-to-december-2023"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/incorporated-companies-in-the-uk-october-to-december-2023/incorporated-companies-in-the-uk-october-to-december-2023</u></a> </p></authorialNote> <authorialNote marker="50"><p> The total register includes <u>all</u> companies required to file accounts with Companies House, whilst on the effective register companies in the course of dissolution are excluded from the count.</p></authorialNote> Therefore, at least 4.8 million companies will need to familiarise themselves with these changes. We do not consider the future cost to new companies. This is because the knowledge that companies will no longer need to hold a register centrally would be absorbed within the overall cost of incorporation.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>4.</num>
          <content>
            <p>At least one individual within each organisation will need to familiarise themselves with these new requirements. In most instances, it will be directors (and equivalents)/PSCs who will do this. We cost this as the opportunity cost of their time valued using the median hourly pay rate (excluding overtime) for managers, directors and senior officials from the Annual Survey of Hourly Earnings (ASHE) in 2023, uplifted by<b> </b>20% to account for non-wage labour costs.<authorialNote marker="51"><p> See: <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/earningsandworkinghours/datasets/occupation4digitsoc2010ashetable14"><u>https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/earningsandworkinghours/ datasets/occupation4digitsoc2010ashetable14</u></a><u> </u>  </p></authorialNote> <authorialNote marker="52"><p> Non-wage costs include sickness, maternity and paternity pay, National Insurance contributions and pension contributions.</p></authorialNote> Using the GDP deflator to bring this into 2019 prices, this is £25.20 per hour.<authorialNote marker="53"><p> See: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/gdp-deflators-at-market-prices-and-money-gdp"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/gdp-deflators-at-market-prices-and-money-gdp</u></a> </p></authorialNote> <authorialNote marker="54"><p> We use 2019 prices to align with the cost assessment produced in the primary legislation impact assessment</p></authorialNote></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>8.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We envision that the familiarising process should be fairly quick and straightforward for companies. Engagement from Companies House suggests that there are a wide range of methods that can be used to make individuals aware of these changes (e.g. letters, emails, web pages etc.). However, Companies House will aim to use digital methods to make it easy and intuitive for companies to understand what is required of them. The familiarisation process should not require training of staff, changes to business processes or briefing sessions for entire teams.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>9.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Familiarisation will not require reading the regulations, Registrar’s rules or guidance, though may involve reading a letter or an email from Companies House. A message that covers an A4 page contains between 400-500 words, and the average reader can read at 200 words per minute. <authorialNote marker="55"><p> <a href="https://www.blackkitetranslations.com/quote/wordcount.php"><u>https://www.blackkitetranslations.com/quote/wordcount.php#:~:text=As%20a%20rule%20of%20thumb,average% 20400%20to%20500%20words</u></a>. </p></authorialNote> <authorialNote marker="56"><p> <a href="https://www.prsa.org/article/how-to-determine-average-reading-time"><u>https://www.prsa.org/article/how-to-determine-average-reading-time</u></a> </p></authorialNote> Overall, the process of familiarising with this policy change is unlikely to be very burdensome. However, taking into consideration that this is a new requirement and may take some additional time for individuals to fully understand – we have created three possible scenarios for familiarisation. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>5.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We envision that it would take individuals anywhere from ten (low) to thirty (high) minutes to understand the policy change - we use twenty minutes as our central estimate.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>6.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We estimate a central cost of £8.40 per entity, which translates to £40.3 million for all entities.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>7.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Table 1 outlines the estimated cost of familiarisation a) per entity and b) Overall for all entities:</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>Table 1: Estimated familiarisation cost </b></p>
            <table uk:widths="1.89in 1.73in 1.73in 1.73in">
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text" />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Low</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Central</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>High</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Cost per entity </b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£4.20</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£8.40</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£12.60</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Total Cost (All entities)</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£20,100,000</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£40,300,000</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£60,400,000</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>8.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Beyond familiarisation, we have not identified any further costs to business. They are still required to provide PSC information to Companies House, which they are doing currently – they just no longer need to keep this information locally as well.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_59">
        <heading>Benefits</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Benefits</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>9.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Keeping a local register involves a range of costs. Therefore, any costs a company will no longer need to incur from keeping a local register would be considered a cost saving/benefit.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>10.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>We identified the following benefits:</p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><b>The cost of maintaining the register: </b>These costs will differ depending on the number of amendments that must be made to the register during a year.<b> </b>Internal data from Companies House shows the average number of PSC changes for all live companies on the register company is 0.38. Therefore, it is arguable that the cost per company to maintain a local PSC register was fairly low.<authorialNote marker="57"><p> See: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/5d431904e5274a699238cf8b/review-implementation-psc-register.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/5d431904e5274a699238cf8b/review-implementation-psc-register.pdf</u></a></p></authorialNote> Evidence from the PSC PIR suggests that the median cost of tasks related to the maintenance of information held on the PSC register since the initial submission of information was £2. This includes: checking information about PSCs, identifying new PSCs, collecting, collating and submitting information about new PSCs. <authorialNote marker="58"><p> Table 3.9 Overall cost of compliance with PSC regulations See: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/5d431904e5274a699238cf8b/review-implementation-psc-register.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/5d431904e5274a699238cf8b/review-implementation-psc-register.pdf</u></a><u> </u></p></authorialNote> Entities will still need to complete these activities to submit the necessary information to Companies House, but will no longer be required for the purpose of maintaining a local register.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><b>Requests to inspect the register: </b>Another cost where a person (either a member or a third party) makes a request to inspect the register. Since this information will be publicly available on the Companies House register, it is unlikely that companies will be contacted directly about their PSC register.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><b>Use of agents: </b>Where an agent is used, they will charge clients a fee – often to provide a package of services. We do not have any data on how many entities use agents nor the fees these agents charge. Therefore, we reference the evidence from the earlier LLP IA to inform our assumptions:<authorialNote marker="59"><p> The Companies and Limited Liability Partnerships (Filing Requirements) Regulations 2016 removed the requirement for LLPs to hold certain registers (of members, of members’ residential addresses, and the register of people with significant control) at either their registered office or an alternative specified location if the information is instead on the public register at Companies House. Given the similarities with this regulation and the changes being made in the PSC amendments – that an entity no longer has to keep a register locally as long as it’s held centrally - its analysis and findings are very relevant. See: <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2016/599/impacts"><u>https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2016/599/impacts</u></a></p></authorialNote></p>
              <block name="embeddedStructure">
                <embeddedStructure>
                  <level>
                    <content>
                      <p><i>“We consider it is unlikely that LLPs which employ agents to undertake a package of entity services (including holding registers) […], we are unable to make an evidence-based assessment about the number of LLPs which would no longer use an agent as a result of the measure. We consider that it is unlikely that LLPs would use agents </i><i><u>only</u></i><i> to hold their registers; generally, holding registers will be part of a package of wider services.”</i></p>
                    </content>
                  </level>
                </embeddedStructure>
              </block>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>11.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Quantifying the scale of these benefits however is challenging due to the lack of available and comparable data. As a result, we use breakeven analysis to estimate the cost savings required.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>12.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Table 2 outlines the estimated minimum benefit/cost-savings required for entities to breakeven over a 10-year appraisal period:</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>Table 2: Estimated annual benefit/cost-savings required </b></p>
